node.title: Investigator Cites Video and Other Evidence Against Jussie Smollett
node.description: A detective told jurors at Mr. Smollett’s trial how the actor had gone from victim to suspect as the investigation unfolded. But the actor’s lawyer suggested the police work was not thorough.

node.title: Teen Allegedly Shot Another at School After Seeing Money Received in Gun Sale Was Fake
node.description: The 15-year-old is facing charges of endangerment, aggravated assault, and weapons violations relating to bringing a weapon on campus.

node.title: Officer Who Shot and Killed Pharrell Williams' Cousin Cleared of Charges By Grand Jury
node.description: Solomon Simmons, a Black Virginia Beach police officer, shot and killed Donovan Lynch after he saw Lynch with a gun near a crowded parking lot.

node.title: In Call for Accountability, Omar Says Boebert Waged 'Attack on Millions of American Muslims'
node.description: On Tuesday, a second video surfaced of Colorado GOP Rep. Lauren Boebert calling a Muslim Congress member a part of the "Jihad Squad."

node.title: The trailer for the Sex and the City reboot has dropped. Here's what we learnt from it
node.description: Fans have been picking at social media posts and paparazzi shots for details about And Just Like That... since it went into production, but the new clips reveal juicy clues about the lives of Carrie, Charlotte and Miranda.

node.title: Alice Sebold's book Lucky shot her to stardom, while a man sat in prison. Now his conviction has been overturned
node.description: Exploring Alice Sebold's experience of being raped and beaten by a stranger when she was a student at Syracuse University, Lucky went on to sell more than a million copies, while Anthony Broadwater – the man at the centre of the story – sat in prison for 16 years.

node.title: 'Nothing compares to being recognised in the soil that you grew in': Rihanna named Barbados National Hero
node.description: Barbados Prime Minister names pop star Rihanna a national hero, telling her: "May you continue to shine like a diamond".

node.title: Police search Marilyn Manson's home as part of sexual assault, domestic violence probe
node.description: Los Angeles police say they seized media storage devices and other items from the home of the musician, who has been accused of abuse by several women.

node.title: WHO advises people over 60 or with underlying conditions to postpone travel to COVID hotspots
node.description: The World Health Organization advises people who are unwell or vulnerable to severe disease or death from COVID-19, including people aged over 60, to postpone travel to hotspot areas.

node.title: Teen who stabbed woman in daylight once chased 'annoying' pet cat with an axe, court hears
node.description: A Melbourne teenager who claims he has no memory of stabbing a woman in the back in broad daylight has been thrown in youth detention over the brazen attack, as it emerged that he once tried to kill a cat with an axe.

node.title: Victorian government introduces some of Australia's 'heaviest' animal activism punishments
node.description: Trespassing onto Victorian farms could attract fines up to $55,000 under new legislation introduced into state parliament today.

node.title: Police hunt man accused of covering up child's murder after court no show
node.description: Authorities urge anyone who knows the whereabouts of Rebyll Oaariki — who was due to appear in court last week but never showed up — to contact them immediately.

node.title: Energy giant AGL slashes its coal and gas workforce
node.description: Australia's largest electricity company slashes its power plant workforce amid a surge of cheap renewable energy.

node.title: Current logic of MIQ system 'doesn't make sense' - Luxon
node.description: National Party leader Chris Luxon says the current managed isolation system for returnees does not make sense and the borders should open with risk management. Audio

node.title: First accuser testifies in Ghislaine Maxwell sex-trafficking trial
node.description: The first alleged victim to testify in Maxwell's trial said she was 14 during her first sexual encounter with Epstein.

node.title: 'Like It Was No Big Deal': Accuser Describes Sexual Encounters With Ghislaine Maxwell
node.description: A woman introduced to the jury as "Jane" testified today that she was sexually abused by Jeffrey Epstein and Maxwell from 1994-1997, starting when she was 14.

node.title: Rāhui on pāua fishing around Waiheke Island starts 1 December
node.description: The scallop, mussel, rock lobster and pāua fisheries around Waiheke Island will close for two years from this week.

node.title: Suite of lending changes come into force today
node.description: Lenders will no longer be able to solely rely on information given by the borrower to show they have made reasonable inquiries about the affordability of loans.

node.title: Forsyth Barr sets up separate funds management operation
node.description: Leading brokerage and investment house Forsyth Barr is setting up separate funds management operation Octagon Asset Management.

node.title: GCSB's new service helps businesses detect cyber threats
node.description: The new service will help private cybersecurity providers protect clients' networks, says the Government Communications Security Bureau.

node.title: Actor hatched 'secret plan' for hate hoax, US court told
node.description: Jussie Smollett hatched a "secret plan" to concoct a hoax hate crime against himself, a court has heard on the opening day of the US TV actor's trial.

node.title: Millions being spent to bring back buzz in Auckland
node.description: The government is pumping $37.5 million this summer to promote travel around Auckland for Aucklanders in a bid to bring back the buzz that quietened over the months-long Covid-19 restrictions.

node.title: Auckland mayor proposes to charge households a climate levy
node.description: Auckland mayor Phil Goff has outlined a plan to charge households a climate levy, so it can increase the amount of buses, ferries, cycling and walking options in the city.

node.title: Man who died after being left at medical centre named
node.description: Police say he was Rangiwhero Toia Ngaronoa, 22, from Gisborne.

node.title: Plans for renewable energy park at Christchurch Airport unveiled
node.description: Christchurch Airport is committing 400 hectares to create a renewable energy park with a solar farm that will generate enough to power 30,000 homes.

node.title: A Climbing Award That May Be a Winner’s Last
node.description: The Piolet d’Or, or Golden Ice Axe, is alpine climbing’s biggest award. But whether it honors or encourages risk is debated in the sport.

node.title: Omicron Variant, in at Least 20 Nations, Spread Earlier Than Was Known
node.description: With evidence growing that a worrisome new coronavirus variant is highly contagious, health officials issued warnings that vulnerable people should not travel.

node.title: Accuser Describes Maxwell and Epstein Ensnaring and Abusing Her at 14
node.description: During the second day of Ghislaine Maxwell’s trial, a woman accused Ms. Maxwell of befriending her when she was a girl, only to join in the sexual abuse that followed.

node.title: A Times editor who attended Oxford recalls a decade-old shooting drill.
node.description: Three teenage students were killed on Tuesday in the school district I graduated from.

node.title: Appeals Court Questions Trump’s Bid for Secrecy on Jan. 6 Papers
node.description: The case presents the novel question of what happens when a current president and a former one disagree about invoking executive privilege.
